\subsection{Geometric and electronic properties of catalyst models}
finite-sized model may be different to an extent from that in the real system because of the size and edge effects. However, it is expected to be qualitatively reliable for using the results acquired from the current model to predict the local chemical properties. Spin multiplicity (SM) numbers were found to be 1 for the $\mathrm{H}_{2} \mathrm{O}_{2}$, 4-PP molecules and graphene sheet; 3 for catalyst model (rGO-4-PP Nc). These selected SM numbers were adopted throughout all calculations.

Fig. 1 shows the optimized geometric structures of graphene $\left(\mathrm{C}_{22} \mathrm{H}_{12}\right)$, catalyst model (rGO-4-PP Nc, $\mathrm{C}_{34} \mathrm{H}_{20} \mathrm{O}_{2}$ ) and 4-PP molecule $\left(\mathrm{C}_{12} \mathrm{H}_{10} \mathrm{O}_{2}\right)$. The optimized graphene has a planar structure with good symmetry, and the 4-PP molecule is connected with graphene by a $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O}-\mathrm{C}$ bond in rGO-4-PP Nc. In addition, the $\mathrm{C}-\mathrm{O}$ bond lengths of $\mathrm{C} 35-\mathrm{O} 34$ and $\mathrm{C} 13-\mathrm{O} 34$ were calculated to be $1.392$ and $1.386 \AA$, respectively, and the $\mathrm{C} 13-$ O34-C35 bond angle was $119.93^{\circ}$ in rGO-4-PP Nc. In contrast, in the 4-PP molecule, the C6-O23 bond length and C6-O-32-H24 bond angle in the corresponding position were calculated to be $1.375 \AA$ and $109.03^{\circ}$, respectively.

